 these texts actually provided alternative-and more appealing-notions of gender than those authorized by the Church, Bartlett redefines women's participation in medieval culture in terms of far greater agency and empowerment than have generally been acknowledged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aAuthorshipxSex differences. 0aDevotional literature, English (Middle)xMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish prose literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aMimesis in literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistory. 0aWomenxBooks and readingzEnglandxHistory. 0aWomenxPrayers and devotionsxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501722080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501722080.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG